         <abstract>
            <p>The concept of the lone-wolf portfolio manager is beginning to come in for some criticism. The current need is for more careful interpretation, taking advantage of the fact that investments are now being made in contemplation of a longer time horizon. One solution is a more or less continuous investment forum in which portfolio managers work side by side with each other and with key research men, relying on each other's areas of special expertise. Although the final investment decision remains with the individual portfolio manager, the result is fuller testing of investment ideas prior to decision. This solution is successful only in an environment that fosters creative interplay of ideas, however, whence the name "group dynamics".</p>
          </abstract>
